# Save Migration Policy

- Save root models must include `version` and UTC timestamp; adding a new field should explicitly account for migration risk.
- Do not consider a save schema change complete until the question "how do old saves upgrade?" has an answer.
- Migration steps should be deterministic and repeatable; loading the same save multiple times must not corrupt data.
- Do not silently fall back on corrupt or missing saves; log contextual `Debug.LogWarning`/`Debug.LogError` messages and include the source version.
- In recoverable cases, choose a safe default or new-save bootstrap flow; in unrecoverable cases, return a failure result to the caller.
- Migration behavior should have at least one old-version fixture or DTO example test; a happy-path save load is not enough.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: No version, parse error is swallowed silently
catch
{
    return new SaveData();
}

// GOOD: Migration decision is version-based
if (save.Version < CurrentVersion)
{
    save = _migrationService.Upgrade(save);
}
```
